{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653695"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:49:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:49:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18591"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18591"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.92,0,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79556"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11323"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64860"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"10389"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26237"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27200"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79556"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents following a stroke. She understands speech but struggles to form words. Brain imaging reveals damage to the posterior inferior frontal gyrus of the left cerebral hemisphere.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the damaged brain region?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Controls tongue movements","Coordinates motor sequences for speech production","Generates emotional responses to speech","Interprets written language","Processes auditory speech signals"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe damaged region is Broca\u0027s area, which primarily \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoordinates motor sequences for speech production\u003C/strong\u003E. This area integrates the complex motor patterns needed to articulate words, explaining why damage results in non-fluent aphasia where patients understand language but struggle to produce speech.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcesses auditory speech signals\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of Wernicke\u0027s area in the temporal lobe\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterprets written language\u003C/strong\u003E - This involves the angular gyrus in the parietal lobe\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerates emotional responses to speech\u003C/strong\u003E - This involves the limbic system, particularly the amygdala\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControls tongue movements\u003C/strong\u003E - Basic tongue movements are controlled by the primary motor cortex and cranial nerve nuclei\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EBroca\u0027s area is typically located in the left hemisphere in right-handed individuals and most left-handed individuals, making it part of the dominant hemisphere for language.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Broca\u0027s area is located in the posterior inferior frontal gyrus of the dominant hemisphere and is crucial for speech production.","Damage to Broca\u0027s area results in non-fluent (expressive) aphasia with preserved comprehension.","Broca\u0027s area coordinates the motor sequences required for speech articulation."],"r